segments.text: And he lectured to us in rather large groups.
He did a fantastic job.
I never would have made it through chemistry without his help, without special help, and probably the special help from the Lord, because it was not a subject that I was particularly interested in.
But I was very interested in English and Bloody Morgan was a noted character there on campus.
He had a great sense of humor and everyone referred to him as Bloody Morgan because he was tough and a great teacher.
He got your attention and kept your attention.
Another one that I was very fond of was E.K.
Spahr.
S-P-A-H-R.
He was, to me, one of the great professors of England.
What did he teach?
He taught English.
English.
Another was an ag-economic professor.
Oh, I should never forget his name.
Dan Russell?

Dan Russell, I want to speak about him a little separately, but Dan was not one, this was the head of the department, a big fella, later helped me get the job with Anderson Clayton, head of the department, which sets my mind right now.
You mentioned Dan Russell, Dan was loved by everyone and his, the work he did for the
poor element of our students who came there wanting an education and just took a chance and came to A&M.

They were told to look up Dan Russell and Dan had a home for boys down there right off campus and all the boys they got a few cows donated and they milked the cows and they turned the butter and they grew the gardens and they lived in that house
and they were a fraternity all of them.
And Dan Russell, we all need to venerate him for the good work he did in those early days, a man that we all love.
Let's see, other good teachers, math.
In math,
That slips my mind.
History?
I reflect on Penberthy.
Yes, please describe Mr. Penberthy.
Mr. Penberthy was one of the most remarkable men that I had ever met and known.
Penny knew more A&M students than anyone on the campus.
He had a fantastic, retentive memory, and he could remember every student's first name, frankly.
But he was one that anyone could go to and get good advice.
He ran a very fine intramural program that was so vital back in those days with no girls, no entertainment, no TV, nothing, and the need for physical activity.
We had softball, we had soccer, we had a little bit of everything, swimming, fencing, tumbling,

And I got interested in tumbling because early on I had learned to walk on my hands and anyone who could walk on their hands and do a handstand and a few things like that just followed into the tumbling team.
So we built a tumbling team there that for a number of years performed at every basketball game during the half.
To this day, people told me, so they went to the basketball game to see the Tumlin team when they did just as much emotional when they did the basketball game.
And Penny arranged for a trip every year for our Tumlin team to Texas, to the women's college at Denton.
And the women's college up there looked forward to that and we went up there and spent the weekend and put on one or two exhibitions for them.
And we entertained Roy and all that dates and stuff.
And describe the social parts of those trips.
Did you meet some attractive young ladies?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, we met some attractive young ladies.
And of course, all of us back in those days at high school, we went to Austin as frequently as we could afford, which wasn't very often.
It was still long distance when I was at college.
And we...
Our girlfriends on the football weekends came in on the train from Austin and went up to the junction.
Into the junction and had to wait for the train coming from Dallas, and they would tie on to that train at Palo Alto Junction.
I remember one time my date, Mary Johnson, who was the daughter of a farmer in San Antonio,
She was in Catholic University and I invited her and she was coming over with a group.
And when the train came in from Dallas, the train from Milano Junction from Austin was not on it.
Uh-oh.
And so, my gosh, we had no, we knew, we learned that Milano Junction, the train from Austin was late and they couldn't wait for it.
So it was sitting at the junction up there, what was that, about 70 miles, 60 miles.
I went to, I dashed down to Casey's.
I said, Mr. Casey, I never ever asked you for a favor, although I had, I'd borrowed a few and five dollars from him here and there, you know, and always paid him back.
I said, could I possibly borrow your car?
I've got a girl, a whole bunch of girls up there.
My line over judge told him what happened.
He threw me the keys.
It was a Buick.
Unfortunately, I think I almost burned it up on the highway going up there.
It picked up all those girls and as many as I could pack on that automobile, I think some of them were hanging on.
We got them back.
Let's see, we were talking about advisors and other important people at A&M.
Were there some characters on the faculty and the staff then?
Well, yes.
You know, one man that I noticed in the military building there, what is it, the new Corps building?
Yes, sir.
There's a picture of all the military heads.
Converse S. Lewis, his picture's not there.
There's no notice of the fact that he was a PMSNT.
And he was a very fine one.
Regular Army officer and a great man.
But he was a stickler.
for certain things, and tough as a boot.
I remember him well.
Now, he was commandant?
He was commandant.
No, no, he was not commandant.
He was a PMS&T.
Oh, PMS&T.
Yeah.
And like in old days, that might have been the same thing.
But the greatest commandant we ever had was Andy Anderson.
Describe him, please, sir.
Andy Anderson and his sweet red-headed wife
two of the most loved people that ever taught on the faculty at Texas A&M University.
Frank Anderson was a track coach, as we all know, and did a fabulous job in the track world, keeping us on the top shelf in that area at all times because he was a man of such work discipline
such character and such love and whatever he did.
But for about two years, he was asked to be common on the cadets.
That would be when we were, I was a junior and senior then him.
So he had both duties for those two years?
Had what?
Did he have both duties, track and?
No, I think he gave up track at that time.
He had, this was a full-time job.
There were several areas where we conflicted as students with Frank.
And there was an uproar, too, about it, but Frank always kept his cool, and what he was trying to do was right.
The students were out of line.
But he weathered the storm and handled it beautifully.
And I have a letter from him in here somewhere.
I'll show you.
As you look back, what were the key courses that you took that were important in your later years?

Well, I was always interested in cotton, having been born in Georgia and picked it over there and picked it here, and then worked for Cotton General and working for Cotton Seed Oil Man in the summertime, for Cotton Freight Broker and for Cotton Compress, going to Europe and studying it.
But it was something that I always wanted to enter into and do as a life work, I thought.
And so I took every cotton course that A&M had.
And because of my background, I did excel and I won the Cotton Fellowship to Europe.
I was so, which was such a great thing.
because it was a challenge.
And Bailey Conant from San Antonio and I, and a man named Hapton, there were three of us, one, two, three.
I was one, Bailey was second, and Hapton was third in the selection process.
And Luther Jones was a leader, selected leader, although this was under John Mogford's agronomies department at the time.
And John was a lead son out of those
groups to Europe for the winners of the Cotton Fellowship, but it was financed by the Cotton Ball, and the Cotton Ball was one of the big social occasions on the campus back in those days.
We always had a named band.
Describe the Cotton Ball.
It was a social event, one of the big social events of the year, if not the social event of the year because we all had
I had one from Corpus Christi.
And they'd come up every two years, my junior and senior year.
And Margaret Yarborough was my date, I remember.
And, but others came from all cities of the state.
And it was, as I say, we had a first-class named band.
for those events, and it was one of the big weekends of the year.
And through it, we raised money for this cotton trip to Europe, plus the fact that Anderson Clayton made up the shortfall.
Anderson Clayton Cotton Company being the largest cotton firm in the world at the time, with headquarters in Houston, very interested in everything cotton-wise at A&M, supported it.
And Will Clayton and his firm were very supportive.
In fact, when we went on that trip to Europe, we were, we sailed out of Boston and we had a great trip over.

We went to England, we went to France, we went to Belgium, we went to Holland, we went to Germany, we went to Switzerland, and all those places, in addition to New York, we studied the marketing of cotton.
And it was a fantastic trip and opportunity.
And I was blessed to enjoy and made a lot of difference in my life.
I went to work for Anderson Clayton when I came out of school.
I didn't stay in it, but of course the war, World War II came along and took me out.
And I never did go back with them, although I had an opportunity when the war was over to go back with them.
And they wanted me back.
but that's another story.
Were there other, we're talking about important courses, other courses that now that you look back on that had an important effect on your future?
Well, the head of the Ag Economics Department, I couldn't think of his name a minute ago, was Dr. Barker.
Barker, B-A-R-K-E-R.
He was
an unusual entrepreneur in his field in that he had contacts with business people all over.
Highly respected in his field.
He helped many, many a young man.
He helped me in many ways.
Took an interest in me.
He taught a class and did a great job.
Where did the faculty and staff members live in those days?
Where did they live?
Yes, sir.
Where were their residences?
You know, they lived in homes adjacent to the campus, mainly, if I recall.
I recall visiting with the Andersons.
They lived over there.
on the south part of the campus there.
Of course, our president, T.O.
Walton, lived right on the campus.
I sat on the swing of his front porch and visited with him as a senior and a junior because he leaned on us, the leaders of the Corps, and we had a very special relationship.
His son was a member of our class, T.O.
Describe President Walton.
President Walton was a large man.
I have a picture of him I can show you here taken with President Roosevelt when the President visited the campus.
They were riding around the campus together and he was showing a very good picture of him.
But T.O.
was a very quiet man and I say T.O.
Dr. Walton.
but a very astute individual, and he had close contacts with F.M.
Law, who at that time, if I recall, was either president of the Association of Former Students, or he later was on the board of, they didn't call it regents then, they called it- Board of Directors.
Huh?
Board of Directors.
Yeah, the Board of Directors of the Governor's, and others, but
He was a good president.
He was, you know, he was a quiet man.
Let's see, you mentioned President, did President Roosevelt come to the campus while you were there?
Yes.
Describe that visit if you remember it.
Well, it was a great event.
We never had seen a president before and he spoke at Guyon Hall or maybe it was an open meeting.
I can't remember, but I do recall
It was a very significant occasion.
Were you all at all aware that Mr. Roosevelt was physically handicapped?
Oh, yes, yes, definitely.
He had a cane, but he was able to get around, and at that time, I don't believe he was in a wheelchair.
Were there some other famous campus visitors you remember during your undergraduate days?
Well, we had...
Yes, we had...
I remember a movie star, Fred McMurray, came and visited the campus and I had the pleasure of being sort of a host for him and he was quite a character and talked to the group and very interesting.
I remember that.

I already of course became governor at the time that we were our junior, our senior year and I was a member of the Ross Volunteers and we went over to take part in the government inauguration and hold the sabers for him and his wife to walk through and I have a good picture of that.
You mentioned the Cottonball Band.
What famous bands or music musicians came to the campus during those years?
Well, we had a man I mentioned earlier, Bailey Conahan, who won the Cotton to a fellowship with me, was from San Antonio.
And he was quite a, thought of an entrepreneur himself in the sense that he
He stayed in touch with these bands and he had a way about him to get their attention and would dickle with them and get them there.
We had all the, some of the top bands of the country back in those days and I swear at my age, my memory sometimes sort of, but name a few of them I'll tell you.
Guy Lombardo, the Dorseys, Kay Kaiser.
Yeah, that's right.
I think we had them all at different times because he, for his junior and senior year, we had several balls and we had that type of top entertainment.
And what did you young men wear and your dates wear to these dances?
Well, the dates, you know, wore their fences,
dresses and we wore our uniforms proudly.
How was a young woman treated at A&M in those days at a dance?
Like a jewel encased.
Do you think they enjoyed coming to those?
Oh yes, they looked forward to it so very much and all of them, whether they were duchesses of the cotton ball or of any significant one of these balls because

one of the reasons they were so successful is that we did not have women on the campus and we needed that type of activity so that we could bring the girls in to the campus for significant occasions and give us a break.
And we would, we had them several times a year.
Where did they stay when they were in town?
We had the inn of the
The Aggieland Inn.
The Aggieland Inn, and we put them in there.
We put away the whole thing for them.
That and the others would stay with various faculty members and families around the campus who would volunteer their homes.
The YMCA played an important role.
What all occurred at the Y or sponsored by the Y?
The YMCA has been a great
I've been a booster of the YMCA ever since I was a kid in Athens, Georgia.
I know the good that it does and it did a great deal of good at A&M.
Few people know that on the second floor of the YMCA they had a loan facility where they made loans to students.
About five dollars to
five hundred dollars or even three or four thousand dollars and they found the money somehow through various sources.
That was before the college took over that operation pretty well as I remember this.
I may be mistaken but I do know that that's why they had that.
We had at that time we had no church on the campus.
We, the YMCA, I'm just trying to think of the name of the, I can see him very plainly, the director of the Y at that time.
Cashin?
Cashin, after Cashin.
Oh, this is after Red Cashin's dead?
Well, I remember Cashin.
I remember Cashin.
Cashin, when he had an assistant, he was very active, tall, old glasses, I can't remember his name.
But they were,

active in many ways and we, the YMCA was a focal point for meetings and of course on the steps of the Y we had our Yale practice right opposite Hart Hall, a law hall there, every, Hart Hall, you know, every weekend.
Was it called Midnight Yale Practice in those days?
Yes.
And who went to midnight Yale practice?
I recall they got the freshmen out, the sophomores, and most everyone who could attend was there.
There would be quite a crowd around.
Let's see, Guyon Hall.
What happened at Guyon Hall?
Well, Guyon Hall, of course, was the one and only place we had on the campus back in the old days for graduation ceremonies or for any.
gathering of that body.
So we're talking about Guy and Hall and what all went on there.
Let's start with the high point.
Was commencement, your commencement there?
My commencement was there.
Please describe your commencement.
Well, my commencement was like any other commencement.
My family, of course, couldn't even come up.
It was
a hardship for them to even be there, but they were extremely proud.
But I think, I remember we had a general present those awards to us, if I'm not mistaken, our graduation awards.
Not a general, can't remember his name, but quite a prominent character.
Now this was May of 1937.
But any time they had any sort of presentation like the former students to the faculty winners of the awards, faculty awards, the mothers clubs used it for their meetings.
The only thing is it was just too small.
It came too small for us.
Were there any religious activities held in Guyon Hall?
Yes, there were.
There were church services held there for a long time, and that brought on the chapel that we dedicated during my administration as president of former students.
I'm very proud of that.
We had a beautiful chapel there, and I wonder today if it's being used effectively.
I understand it's being used for marriages, and many
many services.
I believe it is.
Let's talk about the religious background of the students.
In general, the student body was Protestant, Catholic, what?
Yes, Protestant, Catholic, and many of the boys I know went to church on a regular basis.
Many of them took that Sunday morning to relax and get sort of caught up and write letters and go to Austin, Houston.
Were there any Jewish students then?
Jewish?
Jewish at A&M?
Oh, yes.
How were they treated?
No one, as far as I'm concerned, there was ever any.
whether it was, there wasn't any niggers on our campus, but had they been there, they'd have been treated like anybody else.
Hispanics, one of my closest friends, Eduardo Longoria, he was, of course, from Laredo, and one of the great families in Mexico, but any Hispanic there was, we didn't have any racial difficulties.
Were there any international students?
I don't know of any, but I'm sure there were a few.
But they were usually students who were there working with a doctorate.
They were not in the Corps of Cadets.
Let's see, let's jump back to commencement.
What did you wear to, when you graduated, what did you wear to commencement ceremony?
How many uniforms do I remember?
And every graduate attended?
Oh, yeah.
Let's see.
The big student groups.
If you or I in that era could have held any student office on campus, what would have been the prize honor as an A&M student in that?
For me to be the regimental commander of the cavalry, which I was,
That was my number one goal and I achieved that.

And the other would be to be in the top 10 of the graduation class and be possibly valedictorian, but I really had never had any dream that I could be there, but I made it in the top 10 and we selected, the top 10 selected the valedictorian, who was Jimmy Powell, who was my captain
and they trooped Calvary when I was regimental commander of the Calvary.
Power, P-O-W-E-R?
Power, James A.
Power, Bartlett, Texas.
Now, these, back again about the students, by and large, were these students from any particular section of Texas, or was pretty well the whole state of Texas covered by the student body?
Oh, the whole state of Texas, everywhere from El Paso to, you know,
In Shreveport, we had some out-of-state students, not many, but Jack Creighton was in Shreveport, I recall.

But all parts of the state, that's one of the great things about A&M in that sense that, you know, it took us out of the, you know, just your home jurisdiction area and a statewide school interested in the world.
And they were country and city, from the country and from the city.
All walks of life.
Some poor and some well-to-do.
Absolutely.
The thing about my class of 37, as I see it, it's been a very successful group.
We've had men who
I say vice president of Shell Oil Company, Jim Wilson.
Jack Creighton and Andy Grew, they're two of the greatest geologists in the world today.
Frank Poole, well, he's just a good friend.
He was the last to ask me, but he built the world's largest oil servicing company.
But our people, however you look at them, they were leaders.
to become our commander of the corps, head lead, president of the four-eyes shovel, gravel company.
Bill Kelly.
